# Git Conventions

## Commit Messages — Conventional Commits

Format: `<type>(<scope>): <subject>`

| Type | When to use |
|------|-------------|
| `feat` | New feature or behaviour |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | Code change that is neither feat nor fix |
| `chore` | Tooling, deps, build, config changes |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `ci` | CI/CD pipeline changes |

**Scopes** (pick the closest): `api`, `web`, `worker`, `ui`, `sdk`, `config`, `types`, `prisma`, `auth`, `agents`, `providers`, `chat`, `infra`

```
# ✅ Good
feat(agents): add draft → published status transition
fix(api): prevent system prompt leakage in user chat endpoint
chore(prisma): add workspaceId index on Message table

# ❌ Bad
updated stuff
fixed bug
WIP
```

- Subject: imperative mood, no period, ≤ 72 chars
- Body (optional): explain **why**, not what — separate from subject with a blank line
- Breaking changes: add `!` after scope → `feat(api)!: rename provider enum values`

## Branch Naming

`<type>/<short-description>` — all lowercase, hyphens only

```
feat/agent-tool-calling
fix/sse-reconnect-loop
chore/upgrade-prisma-6
docs/adr-queue-design
```

- Branch off `main` unless told otherwise
- Keep branches short-lived; delete after merge

## PR Rules

- Title follows the same Conventional Commits format as the squash-merge commit
- Body must include: **Summary** (what & why) and **Test plan** (how to verify)
- One logical concern per PR — split if it touches unrelated areas
- Never force-push to `main`

## Monorepo Notes

- Scope commits to the affected app/package — don't use a generic scope when a specific one fits
- Lockfile (`pnpm-lock.yaml`) must be committed together with `package.json` changes
- Never commit `node_modules/`, `.env`, or generated files (`apps/web/.next/`, `dist/`)
